<br>  Hello Bhaskar Chowdhury,<br>

Did you know that you can run commands across visual selection
just like you=E2=80=99re running them in Normal mode?

Let's say we have the following lines written in Perl and we
forgot to append ; to each of them:

my $a
my $b

my $c

We can visually select all 3 lines using Shift-v, and then run a
command:

:normal A;

This will execute a command A; (append ; to the end of a line)
for each selected line.

I've already mentioned the norm[al] command a few weeks ago.
But just to remind you: if you'd like to run the same command
over the entire file content, you could run:

:%normal A;

What if you'd like to comment out the three lines from above?
Simple - select the lines, and then run:

:normal I#

This would insert # at the beginning of each line.

That's all for today Bhaskar Chowdhury

Cheers,
Jovica

